genius.text: “SIR BAUDELAIRE,” the intro to Tyler, The Creator’s seventh studio album, introduces us to Tyler Baudelaire, the character Tyler assumes on CALL ME IF YOU GET LOST. Both Tyler himself and the album’s narrator, DJ Drama, refer to Tyler by the name throughout the record.

With a “corso” being a social promenade or walkway where events and festivals often happen, this song is about Tyler’s social life and influence on people around him. More importantly, this is the first mention of his “entanglement” with his friend’s girl on the album.

“LEMONHEAD” is the third track off Tyler, the Creator’s seventh studio album, Call Me If You Get Lost. The track features Tyler, 42 Dugg, and Frank Ocean showing their bravado by flaunting one another’s opulence and expensive possessions. Details about a collaboration between 42 and Tyler first surfaced through an April 2021 Interview that 42 Dugg gave with Complex.

name: WUSYANAME (feat. Youngboy Never Broke Again & Ty Dolla $ign)

genius.text: On “LUMBERJACK,” the lead single from CALL ME IF YOU GET LOST, Tyler boasts his material wealth and addresses his haters over an abrasive beat that contrasts much of his more melodic production. The song’s instrumental heavily samples the August 1994 Gravediggaz cut “2 Cups of Blood.”

On “MASSA” Tyler calls back to the era of slavery in the United States which took place from its founding in 1776 until 1865 when the Thirteenth Amendment was passed, criminalizing slavery outside of prisons. Tyler uses this time period to exemplify the dramatic contrast between the limitations given to African Americans in the 18th and 19th Centuries, to the modern-day U.S.A. where black men such as Tyler himself have forged great amounts of success for themselves.
In “RUNITUP,” Tyler is discussing the common theme of CALL ME IF YOU GET LOST–success–in light of the past situations that preceded it.
MANIFESTO is track 9 on Tyler, The Creator’s 7th album, CALL ME IF YOU GET LOST.

name: SWEET / I THOUGHT YOU WANTED TO DANCE (feat. Brent Faiyaz & Fana Hues)

genius.text: First released as a teaser on June 14, 2021, “SWEET / I THOUGHT YOU WANTED TO DANCE” is a two-part song that continues the trend regarding every tenth track of the albums from Tyler, The Creator’s discography, which first began with his debut studio album, Bastard. The teaser features Travis Bennett, otherwise known as Taco, a member from the now split-up collective, Odd Future.

This song is exactly as the title suggests – a voice memo of Tyler, The Creator’s mother talking. The main subject covered by his mother, Louisa Whitman, is her defensiveness over Tyler and her evident love for her kids, even to the point of intense confrontation if she feels it is needed.

The second interlude on Tyler’s seventh studio album CALL ME IF YOU GET LOST, this spoken-verse track sees Tyler being grateful for his success and blessings—all his businesses and Camp Flog Gnaw doing amazing, his successful collaborations with companies, his great skincare, and just about every other way he is blessed in life.

name: JUGGERNAUT (feat. Lil Uzi Vert & Pharrell Williams)

genius.text: Tyler, The Creator is joined by Lil Uzi Vert and Pharrell Williams on “JUGGERNAUT,” a stone-cold banger that serves as track fourteen of his album CALL ME IF YOU GET LOST. It features continued contributions from DJ Drama, whose vocals are scattered throughout the album.

Recorded in a single take, “WILSHIRE” sees Tyler tell the story of a failed relationship—from the point of him and his partner first laying eyes upon each other to their eventual breakup. Clocking in at eight and a half minutes, it is the second-longest track on the album, and—excluding the interludes—the only song on CALL ME IF YOU GET LOST to not feature any additional vocals from DJ Drama.

Tyler’s reference to vacation and being able to travel, refers to the front cover of “CALL ME IF YOU GET LOST” , as it shows Tyler’s passport. Being on vacation and the beach is a current theme throughout  this album, which takes a different approach compared to “IGOR” as it includes a more warm and bright approach. The connotation to the “pandemic” on “LEMONHEAD”, could link to the idea that we are able to explore and travel again, and how much Tyler loves to travel, which is emphasised throughout this song.
